{"assignees":[],"body":"## Problem

The `runCommand` function in `src/commands/run.ts` is 950 lines with two major structural issues:

### 1. Sequential and default-mode loops are 80% identical (lines 609-747)

The `--sequential` path (lines 609-699) and the default path (lines 700-747) duplicate the same pattern:
- Look up issue info and worktree
- Start issue logging
- Call `runIssueWithLogging` with 14 positional args
- Record PR info in log
- Complete issue logging

The only difference: `--sequential` stops on failure and has QA-gate checking; default mode continues on failure. This duplication means every change to the issue execution loop must be applied twice.

### 2. `runIssueWithLogging` takes 14 positional parameters

```typescript
// src/lib/workflow/batch-executor.ts:366-380
export async function runIssueWithLogging(
  issueNumber: number,
  config: ExecutionConfig,
  logWriter: LogWriter | null,
  stateManager: StateManager | null,
  issueTitle: string,
  labels: string[],
  options: RunOptions,
  worktreePath?: string,
  branch?: string,
  shutdownManager?: ShutdownManager,
  chainMode?: boolean,
  packageManager?: string,
  isLastInChain?: boolean,
  baseBranch?: string,
): Promise<IssueResult>
```

This is called 3 times in `run.ts` (lines 622, 720, and in batch path) with nearly identical argument lists. The positional nature makes call sites fragile — easy to swap `packageManager` and `baseBranch`, for example.

### 3. Option normalization uses `as any` cast

```typescript
// run.ts:141-142
const cliOpts = options as any;
```

Commander.js converts `--no-X` flags to `{ X: false }`. The workaround casts to `any`, losing type safety for the 6 negated flags.

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] A single execution helper replaces the duplicated sequential/default loops — difference in stop-on-failure behavior is parameterized (not copy-pasted)
- [ ] `runIssueWithLogging` accepts a context object instead of 14 positional params (e.g., `IssueExecutionContext { issue, config, services, worktree, chain }`)
- [ ] All 3 call sites in `run.ts` construct the context object, eliminating positional argument fragility
- [ ] The `as any` cast for Commander.js normalization is replaced with a typed `normalizeCommanderOptions()` function
- [ ] No behavioral change — all existing tests pass, execution order and failure handling unchanged
- [ ] Reduction in `runCommand` line count by removing the duplicated loop (~50 lines)

## Files in Scope

- `src/commands/run.ts` — main refactoring target
- `src/lib/workflow/batch-executor.ts` — `runIssueWithLogging` signature change, `executeBatch` alignment

## Context

```
Sequential loop:  run.ts:609-699  (stop on failure, QA-gate check)
Default loop:     run.ts:700-747  (continue on failure)
Call sites:       run.ts:622, run.ts:720, batch-executor.ts:303+
```

The batch path in `batch-executor.ts:303` (`executeBatch`) has its own 10-param function that partially duplicates `runIssueWithLogging` — this should also adopt the context object but can be a follow-up if needed.

## Design Notes

Suggested context type:
```typescript
interface IssueExecutionContext {
  issueNumber: number;
  title: string;
  labels: string[];
  config: ExecutionConfig;
  options: RunOptions;
  services: {
    logWriter: LogWriter | null;
    stateManager: StateManager | null;
    shutdownManager?: ShutdownManager;
  };
  worktree?: { path: string; branch: string };
  chain?: { enabled: boolean; isLast: boolean };
  packageManager?: string;
  baseBranch?: string;
}
```

For the loop deduplication, consider a helper like:
```typescript
async function executeIssues(
  issues: number[],
  ctx: SharedContext,
  opts: { stopOnFailure: boolean; qaGate: boolean }
): Promise<IssueResult[]>
